A '''pulp polyp''', also known as '''chronic hyperplastic pulpitis''', is a "productive" (i.e., growing) inflammation of [[Pulp (tooth)|dental pulp]] in which the development of [[granulation tissue]] is seen, and is characterised by the overgrowth of the tissue outside the boundary of a tooth's pulp chamber.  A pulp polyp may be found in an open [[Dental caries|carious lesion]] ([[tooth]] cavity), in a fractured tooth, or when a [[dental restoration]] is missing. Due to lack of intrapulpal pressure in an open lesion, pulp [[necrosis]] does not take place as would have occurred in a closed caries case. 

The condition is more commonly seen in children and young adults.<ref name=Chandra2008>{{cite book|author1=Chandra S|author2=Chandra G|title=Oral Medicine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EBqYie7BGsYC&pg=PA39|date=30 May 2008|publisher=Jaypee Brothers Publishers|isbn=978-81-8448-145-7|page=39}}</ref> A good [[vascular]] and immune supply is necessary for such a condition to develop.

